          "body": "If the chapter's positive thesis is Yahweh's sovereignty, its negative warning is pride. Three times the chapter names it: the proud in heart is an abomination (16:5); pride goes before destruction and a haughty spirit before a fall (16:18); it is better to be humble among the lowly than to divide spoil with the proud (16:19). Pride is the disposition that refuses to live within Yahweh's governance — that trusts its own plans (16:1), its own self-assessment (16:2), its own sense of the right way (16:25), and its own power (16:32). The chapter's repeated 'better than' sayings (16:8, 16, 19, 32) are the prescribed antidote: a deliberate ranking exercise that forces the reader to dethrone what pride has enthroned. Better a little with righteousness than great income with injustice (16:8). Better wisdom than gold (16:16). Better humility than proud victory (16:19). Better self-mastery than city conquest (16:32). Each saying asks: what do you actually value most? And each answer is an act of either pride or wisdom."
